ial to present a rare picture of northern slavery on one of the North’s first plantations. The Manor was built in the mid-17th century by British settler Nathaniel Sylvester, whose family owned Shelter Island until the early 18th century and whose descendants still reside in the Manor House. There, as Hayes demonstrates, white settlers, enslaved Africans, and Native Americans worked side by side. While each group played distinct roles on the Manor and in the larger plantation economy of which Shelter Island was part, their close collaboration and cohabitation was essential for the Sylvester family’s economic and political power in the Atlantic Northeast. Through the lens of social memory and forgetting, this study addresses the significance of Sylvester Manor’s plantation history to American attitudes about diversity, Indian land politics, slavery and Jim Crow, in tension with idealized visions of white colonial community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryxTo 1863xNew York (State)xShelter Island. 0aAfrican AmericanszNew York (State)zShelter IslandxHistoryyTo 1863. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)xNew York (State)xShelter Island. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zNew York (State)zShelter Island. 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryxNew York (State). 0aIndians of North AmericazNew York (State)xHistory. 0aPlantation lifexHistoryxNew York (State)xShelter Island. 0aPlantation lifezNew York (State)zShelter IslandxHistory. 0aSlaveryxNew York (State)xShelter Island. 0aSlaveryzNew York (State)zShelter Island. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081478577540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814785775.001.000140